n stereotypes, Salamon and MacTavish reveal the important place that trailer parks hold within the United States national experience. In so doing, they attempt to integrate and normalize a way of life that many see as outside the mainstream, suggesting that families who live in trailer parks, rather than being "trailer trash," culturally resemble the parks’ neighbors who live in conventional homes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aHousing, RuralzUnited States. 0aMobile home livingzUnited States. 0aMobile home parkszUnited States. 0aRural poorxHousingzUnited States. 4aAnthropology. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aUrban Studies.  aaffordable housing, trailer parks, mobile home park life, poor rural families, rural sociology, poverty.1 aMacTavish, Katherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170968540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709685/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles